<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="215" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,486,152,211]" box="[151,337,186,211]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,252,186,211]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1856,1878]" captionTargetBox="[174,1416,202,1827]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[163,1428,193,1835]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Neighbor-Joining trees of p-distances based on 1,044 bp of aligned NADH2 sequence data for individual batoid genera or groups of genera. Taxon names are followed by country, host specimen number (in parentheses), and GenBank number. Outgroup taxa used in each analysis were omitted from the individual trees. Scale bar values indicate substitutions per site. Specimens deposited in the Blue Resources Trust Ichthyology Collection are indicted by stars (see text for details). A. Aetobatus (Aetobatidae). B. Brevitrygon (Dasyatidae). C. Himantura (Dasyatidae). D. Maculabatis (Dasyatidae). E. Neotrygon (Dasyatidae). F. Pastinachus (Dasyatidae). G. Pateobatis (Dasyatidae). H. Urogymnus (Dasyatidae)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2637240/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Figs. 2F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[264,277,187,211]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1923,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,591,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,591,1901]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Neotrygon indica (A–B) and Pastinachus ater (C–E) (Dasyatidae). A. Dorsal surface of mature male (SL-72). B. Dorsal surface of female (SL-24). C. Dorsal surface of mature male (SL-39). D. Scapular denticles of mature male (SL-39). E. Oronasal region of mature male (SL-39)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2637254/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">9</figureCitation>
C–E)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,258,643]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
All three specimens of this species examined were collected from fish markets in Point Pedro in the Northern Province, one from the Munai market (SL-39) and two from the Kottadi market (SL-63 and SL-64). These specimens were morphologically consistent with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macleay" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[716,905,330,355]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[716,905,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Pastinachus ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This identification was supported by the tree resulting from the Neighbor-Joining analysis, which included representation of all five members of this genus. The Sri Lankan specimens formed a tight cluster with our reference specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macleay" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[1053,1130,404,427]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[1053,1130,404,427]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">P. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(KA-35; 
<accessionNumber box="[1246,1363,402,427]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/JQ518815" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">JQ518815</accessionNumber>
) from Indonesian Borneo. These specimens differed from one another by 0–1 bp, and from the reference specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macleay" baseAuthorityYear="1883" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">P. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 4–5 bp. They differed from the reference specimen of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Forsskal" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[877,985,474,499]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sephen">
<emphasis box="[877,985,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">P. sephen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(MM-23; 
<accessionNumber box="[1109,1225,474,499]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/JQ518817" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">JQ518817</accessionNumber>
) from the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[151,220,511,535]" name="Oman" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Oman</collectingCountry>
by 70–79 bp.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,258,643]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
Specimens of this taxon in 
<collectingCountry box="[510,621,546,571]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
have previously been referred to as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Forsskal)" authorityName="Forsskal" baseAuthorityName="Forsskal" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[1037,1383,546,571]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sephen">
<emphasis box="[1037,1261,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Pastinachus sephen</emphasis>
(Forsskål)
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="De Bruin" box="[151,387,582,607]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="De Bruin" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" refId="ref17417" refString="De Bruin, G. H. P., Russell, B. C. &amp; Bogusch, A. (1995) FAO Species Identification Field Guide for Fisheries Purposes. The Marine Fishery Resources of Sri Lanka. FAO, Rome, Italy, 400 pp." type="book" year="1995">
De Bruin 
<emphasis box="[263,320,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">et al.</emphasis>
1995
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moron" box="[400,607,582,607]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Moron" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" pagination="142 - 157" refId="ref19181" refString="Moron, J., Bertrand, B. &amp; Last, P. (1998) A check-list of sharks and rays of western Sri Lanka. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India, 40, 142 - 157." type="journal article" year="1998">
Morón 
<emphasis box="[484,541,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">et al.</emphasis>
1998
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="De Silva" box="[620,787,582,607]" firstAuthor="De Silva" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" pagination="294 - 301" refId="ref17594" refString="De Silva, R. I. (2006) Taxonomy and status of the sharks and rays of Sri Lanka. In: Bambaradeniya, C. N. B. (Ed.), The Fauna of Sri Lanka: Status of Taxonomy, Research and Conservation. The World Conservation Union (IUCN), Sri Lanka and Government of Sri Lanka, Colombo, Sri Lanka, pp. 294 - 301." type="book chapter" year="2006">De Silva 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The latter species is now considered to occur only from the Red Sea to 
<collectingCountry box="[320,415,618,643]" name="Pakistan" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Last, P. R. &amp; Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M." box="[430,611,618,643]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" pagination="345 - 368" refId="ref18604" refString="Last, P. R., Naylor, G. J. P. &amp; Manjaji-Matsumoto, B. M. (2016 a) A revised classification of the family Dasyatidae (Chondrichthyes: Myliobatiformes) based on new morphological and molecular insights. Zootaxa, 4139, 345 - 368. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4139.3.2" type="journal article" year="2016">
Last 
<emphasis box="[487,543,618,643]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first formal report of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Macleay" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[990,1063,620,643]" class="Chondrichthyes" family="Dasyatidae" genus="Pastinachus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ater">
<emphasis box="[990,1063,620,643]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">P. ater</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1132,1245,618,643]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
